I took another try at nginx rewrites and solved my issue. Here is my updated config on the private/internal server (which is not running HTTPS):

```nginx
location /glances/ {
        rewrite /glances/(.*) /$1 break;
        proxy_pass http://localhost:61208;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-For $proxy_add_x_forwarded_for;
        proxy_set_header X-Forwarded-Proto $scheme; #doesn't do anything?
}

location / {
        if ($http_referer ~ "^https?://[^/]+/glances"){
                rewrite ^/(.*) https://$http_host/glances/$1 redirect;
        }
}
```
The trick that did it was adding `https://$http_host/` in the root location's rewrite.

This does mean that glances can only be accessed via the public/external nginx server which is using HTTPS. That's fine for my needs, but it would be nice if all URIs in the web app were protocol-agnostic. It would also be nice if a base path could be set so that the proxy config can be simplified (the double rewrite is a little scary if you think about it...).

