After looking at the `Incremental.fit` problem I'm inclined to generalize this code a bit so that the caller provides a list of models, training and testing data, and a function that gets called after every batch of training data gets processed to determine how to proceed.  That function would accept a dictionary mapping model identity to scoring information, and it would then return a dictionary showing how much further to proceed on each model before checking in again.

```python
def update(score_info):
    """ Something like successive halving for hyperband """
    best = topk(n=len(score_info) / 2, score_info, lambda k: score_info[k]['scores'][-1])
    additional_steps = int(...)
    return {ident: scores_info[ident]['time-step'] + additional_steps for ident in best}

def update(score_info):
    """ Something like Incremental.fit """
    assert len(score_info) == 1
    [d] = score_info.values()
    if any(score > d['scores'][-10] + tolerance for score in d['scores'][-10:]):
        return {ident: d['time-step'] + 1}  # do one more time step
    else:
        return {ident: d['time-step']}  # no more work to do, signals termination

def update(score_info):
    """ Something like RandomSearchCV """
    out = {}
    for ident, d in score_info:
        if any(score > d['scores'][-10] + tolerance for score in d['scores'][-10:]):
            out[ident] = d['time-step'] + 1  # keep evolving this one
        else:
            out[ident] = d['time-step']  # don't evolve this one any further, it's done
```

The full fit function would have the something like the following inputs:

```python
def fit(model, parameter_list, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, update, fit_params, scorer):
    ...
```

This may not cover these cases though.  Critique welcome before I invest time into this.

@ohemorange, I think you misread the issue. They weren't trying to use two certificates in one server block, they were trying to obtain a single certificate for two domains.

With that said, I don't think that's what causes the problem. I was successfully able to obtain a certificate with two domains in one server block, however, I was also able to repo the problem by creating a server block for my desired domain which was also the default server for port 443. The exact server block I used was:
```
server {
    listen 80 default_server;
    listen [::]:80 default_server;
    listen 443 ssl default_server;
    listen [::]:443 ssl default_server;
    include snippets/snakeoil.conf;
    root /var/www/html;
    index index.html index.htm index.nginx-debian.html;
    server_name _ example.com;
    location / { 
        try_files $uri $uri/ =404;
    }   
}
```
What I believe happens is when we create `/etc/letsencrypt/le_tls_sni_01_cert_challenge.conf`, we simply copy the listen directive from the existing server block. The result is we have two server blocks with `listen 443 ssl default_server`, causing the error shown above.

We should add a test case for configurations like this to the compatibility test. After performing a simple grep, it doesn't look like we have one.

@varghesealex90 I can reproduce this issue in `python 2.6.7` and can be solved by using server name identification support which was added to python 2.7.9+ so you have two options:
1) install the dependencies as described [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/18578439/using-requests-with-tls-doesnt-give-sni-support/18579484#18579484).
2) upgrade your python version.
